[[ja:多利思比孤]]
{{ill|Tarishihiko|ja|多利思比孤}} was a king in Japan<ref>{{Cite web |title=「Tarishihiko,was,king,of,Wa,Japan,mentioned,in,the,article,East,Barbarian,section,46,81,st,volume,Suishu,Book,Sui,Dynasty」を使った英語表現・例文・フレーズ｜Cheer up! English |url=http://english.cheerup.jp/corpus/search?name=Tarishihiko+was+king+of+Wa+Japan+mentioned+in+the+article+East+Barbarian+section+46+81+st+volume+Suishu+Book+Sui+Dynasty |access-date=2023-10-19 |website=Cheer up! English |language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Deno |first=Fumiri |date=December 2022 |title=About the King of Han-Winu (漢委奴國王) on the gold seal |url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/25138502221121682 |journal=Journal of Chinese Writing Systems |language=en |volume=6 |issue=4 |pages=265–272 |doi=10.1177/25138502221121682 |issn=2513-8502}}</ref> He had the title of [[Okimi]] and his family name was Ame, so his name has been interpreted as Ame-Tarishi-Hiko.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Waida |first=Manabu |date=1976 |title=Sacred Kingship in Early Japan: A Historical Introduction |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/1062152 |journal=History of Religions |volume=15 |issue=4 |pages=319–342 |issn=0018-2710}}</ref>

