[[ja:多利思比孤]]
{{ill|Tarishihiko|ja|多利思比孤}} was the king of Wa an ancient Japanese Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Deno |first=Fumiri |date=December 2022 |title=About the King of Han-Winu (漢委奴國王) on the gold seal |url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/25138502221121682 |journal=Journal of Chinese Writing Systems |language=en |volume=6 |issue=4 |pages=265–272 |doi=10.1177/25138502221121682 |issn=2513-8502}}</ref> He had the title of [[Okimi]] and his family name was Ame, so his name has been interpreted as Ame-Tarishi-Hiko.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Waida |first=Manabu |date=1976 |title=Sacred Kingship in Early Japan: A Historical Introduction |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/1062152 |journal=History of Religions |volume=15 |issue=4 |pages=319–342 |issn=0018-2710}}</ref>
{{Special characters|description=Included in JIS X 0212 ([[Supplementary Kanji]])}}
{{Wikisource|隋書倭国伝}}
'''Tarishihiko''' (多利思北孤) was the king of {{ill|Wa|ja|倭国}} as recorded in the "Book of Sui" ({{lang|zh|隋書}}), specifically in the section "{{lang|zh|卷八十一 列傳第四十六 東夷 俀國}}". In the ''Book of Sui'', the term "{{Supplementary Kanji Font|俀}}" is used instead of the usual "{{Supplementary Kanji Font|倭}}" seen in other Chinese historical records.<ref>In Japan, "{{Supplementary Kanji Font|俀}}國" is usually regarded as a mistaken rendering of "{{Supplementary Kanji Font|倭}}國".</ref> The account also appears in the ''{{ill|Book of the Northern Dynasties|ja|北史}}''.

== Overview ==
It is recorded that Tarishihiko sent envoys ({{ill|Mission to Sui|ja|遣隋使}}) to {{ill|Sui|ja|隋}} in the 20th year of the ''Kaihuang'' era (600) and the 3rd year of the ''Daye'' era (607).

=== Name ===
The text states, "{{lang|zh|俀王姓阿毎字多利思北孤 號阿輩雞彌}}" ("The king of Wa is surnamed Amabe, has the courtesy name Tarishihiko, and is titled Ahekime").<ref>See {{ill|Great King (Yamato court)|ja|大王 (ヤマト王権)}}.</ref>

=== Wife and Children ===
The text mentions, "{{lang|zh|王妻號雞彌 後宮有女六七百人 名太子爲利歌彌多弗利}}" ("The king's wife is named Kime. The harem includes 600–700 women, and the crown prince is called Rikameitarifuri").

=== Territory ===
The text describes the territory as follows: "{{lang|zh|夷人不知里數但計以日 其國境東西五月行南北三月行各至於海 其地勢東高西下都於邪靡堆 則魏志所謂邪馬臺者也}}" ("The people do not measure distance by ''li'' but by days. The kingdom's borders take five months to traverse east to west and three months north to south, with all directions leading to the sea. The capital, Yamidai, is the same as the Yamatai mentioned in the ''Records of Wei'' (''Weizhi'').")

The text also notes, "{{lang|zh|有阿蘇山 其石無故火起接天者俗以爲異因行祷祭}}" ("There is a mountain called Mount Aso, where rocks inexplicably ignite and connect with the heavens, leading locals to offer prayers and sacrifices").

Regarding the route of the Sui envoy Pei Shiqing, it states, "{{lang|zh|經都斯麻國迥在大海中 又東至一支國又至竹斯國又東至秦王國 其人同於華夏 以爲夷州疑不能明也 又經十餘國達於海岸 自竹斯國以東皆附庸於俀}}" ("The envoy traveled through Tsushima Island in the middle of the ocean, east to Iki, then Tsukushi, and then east to Qinwang. The people resembled those of Hua Xia, and their identity was unclear. Beyond this, the envoy traversed over ten countries to reach the coastline. East of Tsukushi, all were subordinate to Wa").

=== Governance ===
The text records, "{{lang|zh|使者言俀王以天爲兄 以日爲弟 天未明時出聽政 跏趺坐 日出便停理務 云委我弟 高祖曰 此太無義理 於是訓令改之}}" ("The envoy reported that the king of Wa regarded the heavens as his elder brother and the sun as his younger brother. Before dawn, the king would emerge, sit cross-legged, and listen to politics, but he would cease once the sun rose, leaving duties to his 'younger brother.' The Sui emperor Yang Jian disapproved, deeming it unreasonable, and ordered the practice to be changed").

Additionally, "{{lang|zh|内官有十二等 一曰大德 次小德 次大仁 次小仁 次大義 次小義 次大禮 次小禮 次大智 次小智 次大信 次小信 員無定數}}" describes a twelve-rank system of officials ({{ill|Twelve Cap and Rank System|ja|冠位十二階}}).<ref>The order differs from that in ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}}'' and ''{{ill|Jōgū Shōtoku Hōō Teisetsu|ja|上宮聖徳法王帝説}}''.</ref>

